<paper id="1523373677"><title>Comparison of Commitment Schemes Used in Mix-Mediated Anonymous Communication for Preventing Pool-Mode Attacks</title><year>1998</year><authors><author org="Dresden University of Technology" id="2147059803">Elke Franz</author><author org="Dresden University of Technology" id="2511714315">A. Graubner</author><author org="Dresden University of Technology" id="1578628384">Anja Jerichow</author><author org="Dresden University of Technology" id="27868838">Andreas Pfitzmann</author></authors><n_citation>8</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>2102795810</reference><reference>2103647628</reference><reference>2123735079</reference></references><venue id="1131830996" type="C">Australasian Conference on Information Security and Privacy</venue><doi>10.1007/BFb0053726</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.43381">Electronic communication network</keyword><keyword weight="0.44429">Computer security</keyword><keyword weight="0.41521">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.46606">Cryptography</keyword><keyword weight="0.50989">Communication source</keyword><keyword weight="0.47999">Commitment scheme</keyword><keyword weight="0.4564">Electronic funds transfer</keyword><keyword weight="0.43469">Hash function</keyword><keyword weight="0.46227">Public-key cryptography</keyword><keyword weight="0.43374">Tracing</keyword><keyword weight="0.41257">Distributed computing</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>Mixes allow anonymous communication. They hide the communication relation between sender and recipient and, thereby, guarantee that messages are untraceable in an electronic communication network. Nonetheless, depending on the strength of the attacker, several known attacks on mixes still allow the tracing of messages through the network.</abstract></paper>